[[File:Udamikumari Shr Kami detail.jpg|thumb|The ''honden'' at [[Uda Mikumari Shrine]] Kami-gū is made of 3 joined ''Kasuga-zukuri'' buildings]]{{nihongo|'''Kasuga-zukuri'''|春日造}} is a traditional Japanese architectural style which takes its name from [[Kasuga Taisha]]'s ''honden''. It is characterized by the extreme smallness of the building, just 1x1 ''ken'' in size.<ref>The ''ken'' is the distance between one supporting pillar and another, a quantity which can vary from shrine to shrine and even within the same building.</ref> In Kasuga Taisha's case, this translates in just 1.9 m x 2.6 m.<ref name="jaka">JAANUS, [http://www.aisf.or.jp/~jaanus/deta/k/kasugazukuri.htm Kasuga-zukuri], accessed on December 1, 2009</ref> The roof is, as always in shrines, gabled, decorated with ''[[chigi]]'' and ''[[katsuogi]]'', covered with cypress bark and curved upwards at the eaves. Supporting structures are painted vermillion, while the plank walls are white.<ref name="jaka"/> It has a {{nihongo|''tsumairi'' (also called ''tsumairi-zukuri'')|妻入・妻入造}} structure, that is, the building has its main entrance on the gabled side.

After the ''[[nagare-zukuri]]'' style, this is the most common [[Shinto shrine]] style, with most instances in the [[Kansai region]] around Nara<ref name="ko">[http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=248 History and Typology of Shrine Architecture], Encyclopedia of Shinto accessed on November 2009</ref>

